{"title_page": "Midwestern Hayride", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}Leonard sosby bass   Ray Sosby fiddle \n\n'''''Midwestern Hayride''''', sometimes known as '''''Midwest Hayride''''', was an American [[country music]] show originating in the 1930s from radio station [[WLW]] and later from television station [[WLWT|WLW-T]] in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]. During the 1950s it was carried nationally by [[NBC]] and then [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television.<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/288/mode/2up|accessdate=22 March 2020|page=288}}</ref> The program featured live country music (performed mainly by local musicians but on lesser occasions by national stars) and what was then called \"hayseed\" comedy, much of which was the inspiration for the later TV series ''[[Hee Haw]]''. It is credited as the first country music program regularly broadcast by a national network.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rising Costs Bring 'Hayride\" To A Halt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FgsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=%22bonnie+lou%22+state+fair&source=bl&ots=wD93ul2vO9&sig=85M5VitP51opapmA0jzcHnKK_ks&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YtZCVY6qFYi6ggT2-ICIDw&ved=0CEwQ6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q&f=false|website=Google Books|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=1 May 2015|page=14|date=November 10, 1956}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nInspired by the [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]]-based ''[[Louisiana Hayride]]'', the show was originally called '''''Boone County Jamboree''''' (named for nearby [[Boone County, Kentucky|Boone County]] in [[Northern Kentucky]]). ''Midwestern Hayride'' was first broadcast before 1937 and was carried live on radio each Saturday evening through the early 1970s.\n\nTelevision station WLW-T came on the air in 1948, sharing larger quarters with radio station WLW in the former Elks Building, re-christened Crosley Square. It eventually became the originating studio for the regional network Avco Broadcasting Corporation, which included [[WXIA|WLW-A]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[WDTN|WLW-D]] in Dayton, [[WCMH-TV|WLW-C]] in Columbus and later [[WTHR|WLW-I]] in Indianapolis (after WLW-A was sold) when the program moved to television in the early 1950s. Then originating from WLW-T, ''Midwestern Hayride'' was simulcast on WLW radio until the early 1960s, then was revived in the mid-60s. At the show's peak there was a one-year waiting list for tickets to be in the audience (100 people was the limit for each weekly show).\n\nIn 1951, ''Midwestern Hayride'' was picked up by NBC-TV as a summer replacement for [[Sid Caesar]]'s ''[[Your Show of Shows]]''. NBC aired it each of the following summers through 1956, except 1953. ABC-TV then carried it during the summers of 1957&ndash;59. For much of its television run ''MH'' was hosted by Dean Richards, lead vocalist of The Lucky Pennies, a local singing group.  Richards also introduced a \"Polka Time\" segment (geared to Cincinnati's German heritage and its local breweries) aired near the program's close until 1969, when he was replaced by [[Henson Cargill]] riding on the success of his hit song \"Skip a Rope\".\n\nBy the early 1970s, then-16 year ''MH'' veteran [[Kenny Price]], a popular musician and comedian nicknamed The Round Mound of Sound, had a string of country hits for [[RCA Records]] including local favorite \"[[The Sheriff of Boone County]]\".  On the strength of those hits, Price was picked to be the new host of the show, which by then had shortened its name to ''Hayride'' (''Louisiana Hayride'' had succumbed to rock and roll's popularity and left the airwaves by 1960).\n\nLike many other locally produced shows of the day, ''Hayride'' become increasingly more expensive to produce, and WLW-TV executives decided to bring the show to an end in 1972.  Kenny Price became a regular on Nashville-based ''Hee Haw'' four years later and remained there until his death in 1987.\n\nIn 2009, [[WYNS-FM]], a low-power community FM station in [[Waynesville, Ohio]] (north of Cincinnati), announced it would commence a similar live weekly country music broadcast, ''The Ohio Hayride'', beginning May 15, 2010. The local program, possibly the first of its kind since the demise of ''Hayride'', was to feature local musicians as well as country music artists from past decades. The program was also to air on WPFB-AM in Middletown, Ohio and stream from the WYNS station website at www.hybridfm.net.\n\n== Performers ==\n{|\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* Herb & Kay Adams\n* Vic Bellamy\n* Bobby Bobo\n* [[Girls of the Golden West (country music duo)|Girls of The Golden West]]\n* Judy Perkins\n* Skeeter Bonn\n* [[Bonnie Lou]]\n* Phyllis Brown\n* Brown's Ferry Four\n* Slim Bryant\n* Chris \"Milkman\" Scheid\n* [[Jerry Byrd]]\n* The Country Briarhoppers \n* [[Cowboy Copas]]\n* Hugh Cross\n* Lazy Jim Day\n* [[The Delmore Brothers]]\n* [[The DeZurik Sisters]]\n* [[Little Jimmy Dickens]]\n* Smokey Duvall\n* Too Slim Bobby Simpson\n* [[Clay Eager]]\n* Louie Ennis\n* [[Shug Fisher]]\n* Sonny Fleming\n* Betty Foley<ref>Barry McCloud (1995) ''[http://www.folklib.net/index/discog/bibliog.shtml#fu Definitive Country: The Ultimate Encyclopedia of Country Music and Its Performers, p. 290]'', {{ISBN|0-399-52144-5}}</ref>\n* [[Red Foley]]\n* [[The Duke of Paducah|Whitey Ford]]\n* Geer Sisters\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* Charlie Gore and the Rangers\n* Otto Gray\n* Rudy Hanson\n* Ted \"Gas House\" Hensley\n* Billy Holmes\n* [[Salty Holmes]]\n* [[Homer and Jethro]]\n* The Hometowners\n* Louie Innis\n* Rome Johnson\n* [[Tommy Jackson (musician)|Tommy Jackson]]\n* [[Grandpa Jones]]\n* Lee Jones\n* Judy and Jen\n* Junior Kentucky Briarhoppers\n* Harpo Kidwell\n* [[Bradley Kincaid]]\n* Slim King\n* John Lair\n* [[Freddie Langdon]]\n* [[Dixie Lee]]\n* Ernie Lee\n* [[Freddie Langdon]]\n* Pa and Ma McCormick\n* [[Clayton McMichen]]\n* [[Joe Maphis]]\n* Sleepy Marlin\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* The Mid-Westerners\n* Carl Moore\n* Natchee the Indian Fiddler\n* Jay Near\n* [[Willie Nelson]]\n* Mattie O'Neil\n* Jimmy Osborne\n* [[Dolly Parton]]\n* [[Hank Penny]]\n* Judy Perkins\n* Prairie Ramblers\n* [[Kenny Price]]\n* The Kentucky Boys\n* [[Riley Puckett]]\n* Rangers Quartet\n* Brownie Reynolds\n* Dean Richards\n* Jerry Richards\n* [[Tex Ritter]]\n* Kenny Roberts\n* Jack Rogers\n* Mimi Roman\n* Buddy Ross\n* Helen and Billy Scott\n* Coleen Sharp\n* Billy Strickland\n* Swannee River Boys\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* Garry \"2 Tall\" Grammell\n* Willie Thall\n* The Lucky Pennies\n* The Three Ks\n* The Trailhands\n* [[Merle Travis]]\n* Red Turner\n* Zeke Turner\n* [[Porter Wagoner]]\n* Tommy Watson\n* Tex Walls\n* Penny West\n* Joy Whitaker\n* Willis Brothers\n* Dom Rockin Horse Mason\n* [[Jim Wood (fiddler)|Jim Wood]]\n* Helen Diller\n* Chuck Wright\n* John \"Gut Bucket\" Halcomb\n* Zeke and Bill\n* Jeannie Hogan\n* [[Judy Martin (singer)|Judy Martin]] (Accordion on Saturday broadcast)\n* Creola Faye Knear-Dorning (midwestern Dancer)\n* Ky. Briarhoppers\n|}\n\n==Network television broadcast history==\n<small>(all times are [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]&mdash;all running times include [[television advertising|commercial]] breaks)</small>\n<br>  \n'''NBC''':\n\n*June 15&ndash;September 1951:  Saturday 9&ndash;10 p.m. \n*June&ndash;September 1952:  Tuesday 8&ndash;9 p.m.\n*June&ndash;September 1954: Tuesday 8&ndash;8:30&nbsp;p.m.\n*May&ndash;September 1955: Friday 8&ndash;8:30&nbsp;p.m.\n*[[1955\u201356 United States network television schedule#Wednesday|September 1955&ndash;June 1956: Wednesday 10&ndash;10:30 p.m.]]\n\nThe program was also occasionally carried by NBC outside of [[prime time]] during the regular [[TV season|season]].<ref>{{citation|first1=Tim|last1=Brooks|first2=Earle|last2=Marsh|title=[[The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network TV Shows]]|publisher=Ballantine Books|year=1992|isbn=0-345-37792-3}}</ref>\n\n'''ABC''':\n\n*July&ndash;October 1957: Sunday 9:30&ndash;10 p.m.\n*January&ndash;September 1958:  Saturday 10&ndash;10:30&nbsp;p.m.\n*May&ndash;September 6, 1959:  Sunday 7&ndash;7:30&nbsp;p.m.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n\n* {{citation|first1=Tim|last1=Brooks|first2=Earle|last2=Marsh|title=[[The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network TV Shows]]|publisher=Ballantine Books|year=1992|isbn=0-345-37792-3}}.\n* [http://www.hillbilly-music.com/programs/story/index.php?prog=180 Hillbilly-Music.com]\n* [http://www.traditionalmusic.co.uk/country-history/History-Country-Western%20-%200271.htm Encyclopedia of Country, Western & Gospel Music]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0479329  Midwestern Hayride television series information at Internet Movie Database]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rX4O3m_Ywj8 YouTube video clip of ''Midwestern Hayride'' singer Bonnie Lou at 1973 Ohio State Fair]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52bfk2dcaRM YouTube kinescope clip of Mimi Roman performing \"Mama Says\" on ''Midwestern Hayride'']\n* [http://www.keepinitcountryfarm.com Official website of ''The Ohio Hayride'' radio program on WYNS-FM and WPFB-AM]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midwestern Hayride}}\n[[Category:1930s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:1940s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:1950s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:1960s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:American country music radio programs]]\n[[Category:Country music television series]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Music of Cincinnati]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n'''''Midwestern Hayride''''', sometimes known as '''''Midwest Hayride''''', was an American [[country music]] show originating in the 1930s from radio station [[WLW]] and later from television station [[WLWT|WLW-T]] in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]. During the 1950s it was carried nationally by [[NBC]] and then [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] television.<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/288/mode/2up|accessdate=22 March 2020|page=288}}</ref> The program featured live country music (performed mainly by local musicians but on lesser occasions by national stars) and what was then called \"hayseed\" comedy, much of which was the inspiration for the later TV series ''[[Hee Haw]]''. It is credited as the first country music program regularly broadcast by a national network.<ref>{{cite web|title=Rising Costs Bring 'Hayride\" To A Halt|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FgsEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA18&lpg=PA18&dq=%22bonnie+lou%22+state+fair&source=bl&ots=wD93ul2vO9&sig=85M5VitP51opapmA0jzcHnKK_ks&hl=en&sa=X&ei=YtZCVY6qFYi6ggT2-ICIDw&ved=0CEwQ6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q&f=false|website=Google Books|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=1 May 2015|page=14|date=November 10, 1956}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nInspired by the [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]]-based ''[[Louisiana Hayride]]'', the show was originally called '''''Boone County Jamboree''''' (named for nearby [[Boone County, Kentucky|Boone County]] in [[Northern Kentucky]]). ''Midwestern Hayride'' was first broadcast before 1937 and was carried live on radio each Saturday evening through the early 1970s.\n\nTelevision station WLW-T came on the air in 1948, sharing larger quarters with radio station WLW in the former Elks Building, re-christened Crosley Square. It eventually became the originating studio for the regional network Avco Broadcasting Corporation, which included [[WXIA|WLW-A]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]], [[WDTN|WLW-D]] in Dayton, [[WCMH-TV|WLW-C]] in Columbus and later [[WTHR|WLW-I]] in Indianapolis (after WLW-A was sold) when the program moved to television in the early 1950s. Then originating from WLW-T, ''Midwestern Hayride'' was simulcast on WLW radio until the early 1960s, then was revived in the mid-60s. At the show's peak there was a one-year waiting list for tickets to be in the audience (100 people was the limit for each weekly show).\n\nIn 1951, ''Midwestern Hayride'' was picked up by NBC-TV as a summer replacement for [[Sid Caesar]]'s ''[[Your Show of Shows]]''. NBC aired it each of the following summers through 1956, except 1953. ABC-TV then carried it during the summers of 1957&ndash;59. For much of its television run ''MH'' was hosted by Dean Richards, lead vocalist of The Lucky Pennies, a local singing group.  Richards also introduced a \"Polka Time\" segment (geared to Cincinnati's German heritage and its local breweries) aired near the program's close until 1969, when he was replaced by [[Henson Cargill]] riding on the success of his hit song \"Skip a Rope\".\n\nBy the early 1970s, then-16 year ''MH'' veteran [[Kenny Price]], a popular musician and comedian nicknamed The Round Mound of Sound, had a string of country hits for [[RCA Records]] including local favorite \"[[The Sheriff of Boone County]]\".  On the strength of those hits, Price was picked to be the new host of the show, which by then had shortened its name to ''Hayride'' (''Louisiana Hayride'' had succumbed to rock and roll's popularity and left the airwaves by 1960).\n\nLike many other locally produced shows of the day, ''Hayride'' become increasingly more expensive to produce, and WLW-TV executives decided to bring the show to an end in 1972.  Kenny Price became a regular on Nashville-based ''Hee Haw'' four years later and remained there until his death in 1987.\n\nIn 2009, [[WYNS-FM]], a low-power community FM station in [[Waynesville, Ohio]] (north of Cincinnati), announced it would commence a similar live weekly country music broadcast, ''The Ohio Hayride'', beginning May 15, 2010. The local program, possibly the first of its kind since the demise of ''Hayride'', was to feature local musicians as well as country music artists from past decades. The program was also to air on WPFB-AM in Middletown, Ohio and stream from the WYNS station website at www.hybridfm.net.\n\n== Performers ==\n{|\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* Herb & Kay Adams\n* Vic Bellamy\n* Bobby Bobo\n* [[Girls of the Golden West (country music duo)|Girls of The Golden West]]\n* Judy Perkins\n* Skeeter Bonn\n* [[Bonnie Lou]]\n* Phyllis Brown\n* Brown's Ferry Four\n* Slim Bryant\n* Chris \"Milkman\" Scheid\n* [[Jerry Byrd]]\n* The Country Briarhoppers \n* [[Cowboy Copas]]\n* Hugh Cross\n* Lazy Jim Day\n* [[The Delmore Brothers]]\n* [[The DeZurik Sisters]]\n* [[Little Jimmy Dickens]]\n* Smokey Duvall\n* Too Slim Bobby Simpson\n* [[Clay Eager]]\n* Louie Ennis\n* [[Shug Fisher]]\n* Sonny Fleming\n* Betty Foley<ref>Barry McCloud (1995) ''[http://www.folklib.net/index/discog/bibliog.shtml#fu Definitive Country: The Ultimate Encyclopedia of Country Music and Its Performers, p. 290]'', {{ISBN|0-399-52144-5}}</ref>\n* [[Red Foley]]\n* [[The Duke of Paducah|Whitey Ford]]\n* Geer Sisters\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* Charlie Gore and the Rangers\n* Otto Gray\n* Rudy Hanson\n* Ted \"Gas House\" Hensley\n* Billy Holmes\n* [[Salty Holmes]]\n* [[Homer and Jethro]]\n* The Hometowners\n* Louie Innis\n* Rome Johnson\n* [[Tommy Jackson (musician)|Tommy Jackson]]\n* [[Grandpa Jones]]\n* Lee Jones\n* Judy and Jen\n* Junior Kentucky Briarhoppers\n* Harpo Kidwell\n* [[Bradley Kincaid]]\n* Slim King\n* John Lair\n* [[Freddie Langdon]]\n* [[Dixie Lee]]\n* Ernie Lee\n* [[Freddie Langdon]]\n* Pa and Ma McCormick\n* [[Clayton McMichen]]\n* [[Joe Maphis]]\n* Sleepy Marlin\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* The Mid-Westerners\n* Carl Moore\n* Natchee the Indian Fiddler\n* Jay Near\n* [[Willie Nelson]]\n* Mattie O'Neil\n* Jimmy Osborne\n* [[Dolly Parton]]\n* [[Hank Penny]]\n* Judy Perkins\n* Prairie Ramblers\n* [[Kenny Price]]\n* The Kentucky Boys\n* [[Riley Puckett]]\n* Rangers Quartet\n* Brownie Reynolds\n* Dean Richards\n* Jerry Richards\n* [[Tex Ritter]]\n* Kenny Roberts\n* Jack Rogers\n* Mimi Roman\n* Buddy Ross\n* Helen and Billy Scott\n* Coleen Sharp\n* Billy Strickland\n* Swannee River Boys\n| width=\"22%\" valign=\"top\"|\n* Garry \"2 Tall\" Grammell\n* Willie Thall\n* The Lucky Pennies\n* The Three Ks\n* The Trailhands\n* [[Merle Travis]]\n* Red Turner\n* Zeke Turner\n* [[Porter Wagoner]]\n* Tommy Watson\n* Tex Walls\n* Penny West\n* Joy Whitaker\n* Willis Brothers\n* Dom Rockin Horse Mason\n* [[Jim Wood (fiddler)|Jim Wood]]\n* Helen Diller\n* Chuck Wright\n* John \"Gut Bucket\" Halcomb\n* Zeke and Bill\n* Jeannie Hogan\n* [[Judy Martin (singer)|Judy Martin]] (Accordion on Saturday broadcast)\n* Creola Faye Knear-Dorning (midwestern Dancer)\n* Ky. Briarhoppers\n|}\n\n==Network television broadcast history==\n<small>(all times are [[Eastern Time Zone|Eastern Time]]&mdash;all running times include [[television advertising|commercial]] breaks)</small>\n<br>  \n'''NBC''':\n\n*June 15&ndash;September 1951:  Saturday 9&ndash;10 p.m. \n*June&ndash;September 1952:  Tuesday 8&ndash;9 p.m.\n*June&ndash;September 1954: Tuesday 8&ndash;8:30&nbsp;p.m.\n*May&ndash;September 1955: Friday 8&ndash;8:30&nbsp;p.m.\n*[[1955\u201356 United States network television schedule#Wednesday|September 1955&ndash;June 1956: Wednesday 10&ndash;10:30 p.m.]]\n\nThe program was also occasionally carried by NBC outside of [[prime time]] during the regular [[TV season|season]].<ref>{{citation|first1=Tim|last1=Brooks|first2=Earle|last2=Marsh|title=[[The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network TV Shows]]|publisher=Ballantine Books|year=1992|isbn=0-345-37792-3}}</ref>\n\n'''ABC''':\n\n*July&ndash;October 1957: Sunday 9:30&ndash;10 p.m.\n*January&ndash;September 1958:  Saturday 10&ndash;10:30&nbsp;p.m.\n*May&ndash;September 6, 1959:  Sunday 7&ndash;7:30&nbsp;p.m.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n\n* {{citation|first1=Tim|last1=Brooks|first2=Earle|last2=Marsh|title=[[The Complete Directory to Prime Time Network TV Shows]]|publisher=Ballantine Books|year=1992|isbn=0-345-37792-3}}.\n* [http://www.hillbilly-music.com/programs/story/index.php?prog=180 Hillbilly-Music.com]\n* [http://www.traditionalmusic.co.uk/country-history/History-Country-Western%20-%200271.htm Encyclopedia of Country, Western & Gospel Music]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0479329  Midwestern Hayride television series information at Internet Movie Database]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rX4O3m_Ywj8 YouTube video clip of ''Midwestern Hayride'' singer Bonnie Lou at 1973 Ohio State Fair]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52bfk2dcaRM YouTube kinescope clip of Mimi Roman performing \"Mama Says\" on ''Midwestern Hayride'']\n* [http://www.keepinitcountryfarm.com Official website of ''The Ohio Hayride'' radio program on WYNS-FM and WPFB-AM]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midwestern Hayride}}\n[[Category:1930s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:1940s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:1950s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:1960s American radio programs]]\n[[Category:American country music radio programs]]\n[[Category:Country music television series]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Music of Cincinnati]]\n", "name_user": "99.203.1.204", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midwestern_Hayride"}
{"title_page": "Brown Eyed Girl", "text_new": "{{about|the song|the South Korean girl group|Brown Eyed Girls}}\n{{about|the Van Morrison song|the song, \"Brown-Eyed Girl\"|The Golliwogs}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brown Eyed Girl\n| cover      = BrownEyedGirl.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Dutch 7-inch vinyl single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Van Morrison]]\n| album      = [[Blowin' Your Mind!]]\n| B-side     = Goodbye Baby\n| released   = {{Start date|1967|06}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 28 March 1967\n| studio     = [[A & R Recording|A & R]], New York City\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 3:05\n| label      =\n*[[London Records|London]] (UK)\n*[[Bang Records|Bang]] (US)\n| writer     = Van Morrison\n| producer   = [[Bert Berns]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Ro Ro Rosey\n| next_year  = 1967\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|UfmkgQRmmeE|\"Brown Eyed Girl\"}}\n | type   = single\n | header = Audio\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Brown Eyed Girl'''\" is a song by Northern Irish singer and songwriter [[Van Morrison]]. Written by Morrison and recorded in March 1967 for [[Bang Records]] owner and producer [[Bert Berns]], it was released as a single in June of the same year on the Bang label, peaking at number 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song spent a total of sixteen weeks on the chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/van-morrison|title=Van Morrison Brown Eyed Girl Chart History|website=Billboard}}</ref> It featured [[the Sweet Inspirations]] singing [[Backing vocalist|back-up vocals]] and is considered to be Van Morrison's [[signature song]].<ref>Yorke, Into the Music, p. 42</ref> \"Brown Eyed Girl\" has remained a staple on [[classic rock]] radio, and has been covered by hundreds of bands over the decades. This hit was written about Grace Modica of Long Island New York.\n\n==Recording and title==\nAfter finishing his contract with [[Decca Records]] and the mid-1966 break-up of his band, [[Them (band)|Them]], Morrison returned to Belfast seeking a new recording company. When he received a phone call from [[Bert Berns]], owner of [[Bang Records]], who had produced a number of recordings with Them, he flew to New York City and hastily signed a contract (which biographer [[Clinton Heylin]] says probably still gives him sleepless nights).<ref>Heylin, ''Can You Feel the Silence''. p.144-147</ref> During a two-day recording session starting 28 March 1967, he recorded eight songs intended to be used as four singles.<ref>Turner, Too Late to Stop Now. p.76</ref> The recording session took place at A & R Studios and \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was captured on the 22nd take on the first day.<ref>Heylin, Can You Feel the Silence?, p. 152</ref> Of the musicians Berns had assembled, there were three guitarists \u2013 [[Eric Gale]], [[Hugh McCracken]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music-illuminati.com/interview-jeff-barry/|title=Interview: Jeff Barry|publisher=music-illuminati.com|date=29 January 2010|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref><ref>Rogan, ''No Surrender''. p.199</ref> and [[Al Gorgoni]] \u2013 plus bassist [[Russ Savakus]], pianist [[Paul Griffin (musician)|Paul Griffin]] and drummer [[Gary Chester]].<ref>Heylin, ''Can You Feel the Silence?''. p. 150</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gary-chester.com/biography.html |title=Meet Gary |publisher=gary-chester.com |accessdate=21 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116225941/http://www.gary-chester.com/biography.html |archivedate=16 January 2012 }}</ref> It was released as a single in mid-June 1967.<ref>Rogan, ''No Surrender''. p.201</ref>\n\nOriginally titled \"Brown-Skinned Girl\",<ref name = \"SpenceCut103\">{{cite web|url=http://www.folkways.si.edu/joseph-spence/the-complete-folkways-recordings-1958/caribbean-world/music/album/smithsonian|title=Smithsonian Folkways - Joseph Spence: The Complete Folkways Recordings, 1958|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> Morrison changed it to \"Brown Eyed Girl\" when he recorded it. Morrison remarked on the title change: \"That was just a mistake. It was a kind of Jamaican song. Calypso. It just slipped my mind [that] I changed the title.\"<ref name=\"CollisPage81\">Collis, Inarticulate Speech of the Heart. p81.</ref> \"After we'd recorded it, I looked at the tape box and didn't even notice that I'd changed the title. I looked at the box where I'd lain it down with my guitar and it said 'Brown Eyed Girl' on the tape box. It's just one of those things that happen.\"<ref>Rogan, No Surrender. p.43</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Independent on Sunday, ''Decoded songs and their meanings''|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/decoded-songs-and-their-meanings-2139733.html|date= 21 November 2010|accessdate=24 October 2013|location=London|work=The Independent|first=Paul|last=Bignell}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n|filename=Van Morrison-Brown Eyed Girl.ogg\n|title=\"Brown Eyed Girl\"\n|description=An 18-second audio sample of Van Morrison's \"Brown Eyed Girl\"\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nThe song's nostalgic lyrics about a former love were considered too suggestive at the time to be played on many [[Radio broadcasting|radio stations]]. A radio-edit of the song was released which removed the lyrics \"making love in the green grass\", replacing them with \"laughin' and a-runnin', hey hey\" from a previous verse. This edited version appears on some copies of the compilation album ''[[The Best of Van Morrison]]''. However, the remastered album seems{{clarify|date=October 2013}} to have the [[Thomas Bowdler|bowdlerised]] lyrics in the packaging but the original \"racy\" lyrics on the disc. Lyrically, it \"shows early hints of the idealized pastoral landscapes that would flow through his songs through the decades, a tendency that links him to the Romantic poets, whom Morrison has cited as an influence\" according to music journalist Erik Hage.<ref>Hage, ''The Words and Music of Van Morrison'', pp. 33-34</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nBecause of a contract he signed with Bang Records without legal advice, Morrison states that he has never received any [[royalties]] for writing or recording this song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.martaypix.com/VAN_at_Rancho_Nicasio/VAN_Rancho.html|title=Van Morrison at Rancho Nicasio|publisher=martaypix.com|accessdate= 27 August 2008}}</ref> The contract made him liable for virtually all recording expenses incurred for all of his Bang Records recordings before royalties would be paid, and after those expenses were recouped, the revenue would become the \"subject of some highly creative accounting\".{{attribution needed|date=March 2018}}<ref>Heylin, Can You Feel the Silence. p.148</ref> Morrison vented frustration about this unjust contract in his sarcastic nonsense song \"The Big Royalty Check\". Morrison has stated that \"Brown Eyed Girl\" is not among his favourite songs, remarking \"it's not one of my best. I mean I've got about 300 songs that I think are better\".<ref>{{Cite video |title = TIME Magazine Interviews: Van Morrison | publisher = [[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |date =26 February 2009 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVHbUPNcTiU |minutes=4:14 |accessdate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nTo capitalise on the success of the single, producer Berns assembled the album ''[[Blowin' Your Mind!]]'' without Morrison's input or knowledge. Released in September 1967, the album contained the single as its lead-off track as well as songs recorded by Morrison at the March recording sessions for Berns. The album peaked at No. 182 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].\n\n==Legacy==\nMorrison's original recording of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" remains widely familiar today, as the uncensored version is regularly played by many \"[[oldies]]\" and \"[[classic rock]]\" radio stations. In 2005, Morrison received a Million-Air certificate by [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI]] as a \"Top European Writer\" for reaching 7 million US radio and television airplays for \"Brown Eyed Girl\" and again in 2007, Morrison was awarded another Million-Air certificate by BMI for 8 million air plays of \"Brown Eyed Girl\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/334626|title=BMI Honors Top European Writers|date=28 November 2005|accessdate=23 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114065908/http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/334626|archive-date=14 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/535578|title=Peter Gabriel Receives Top Honor at BMI Awards|publisher=BMI|date=16 October 2007|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> In 2009, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was at the top of the list for most played songs at the BMI London awards winning a Million-Air certificate for 9 million air plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/539750|title=BMI London Awards|date=9 October 2009|publisher=BMI|accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref> In 2011, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" joined an elite group of songs as it was honoured for having 10 million US radio air plays and therefore becoming one of the ten songs that have been registered with BMI that have received that number of radio plays.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/my-10-million-radio-plays-brown-eyed-girl-2896314.html|title=My 10 million radio plays Brown Eyed Girl|journal=[[Irish Independent]]|date=5 October 2011|accessdate=21 January 2011}}</ref> As of 2015, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" remains the most downloaded and most played song of the entire 1960s decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6472929/revisionist-history-valentines-day-edition-captain-tennille |title=Revisionist History, Valentine's Day Edition: Captain & Tennille Crunches Aerosmith, Van Morrison Boots Lulu |last=Appel |first=Rich |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=14 February 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Williams (Crawdaddy! creator)|Paul Williams]] included \"Brown Eyed Girl\" in his book ''Rock and Roll: The 100 Best Singles'',<ref>Williams, Rock and Roll: The 100 Best Singles. p. 122</ref> writing that:\n\n<blockquote>\"I was going to say this is a song about sex, and it is, and a song about youth and growing up, and memory, and it's also\u2014very much and very wonderfully\u2014a song about singing.\"</blockquote>\n\nThis song proved to be the impetus for Morrison's career. It was his first single after leaving his position as lead singer for the [[Belfast]]-formed [[Them (band)|Them]] and led to his relocation to the United States and an eventual [[recording contract|contract]] with [[Warner Bros. Records]], where he recorded his career-defining [[album]], ''[[Astral Weeks]]''.\n\n==Critical acclaim and influence==\n[[Dave Marsh]] in his 1989 book, ''The Heart of Rock and Soul, The 1001 Greatest Singles Ever'', rated it No.&nbsp;386.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/dmarsh_1001.htm |title= Dave Marsh the 1001 greatest Singles Ever |publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=8 April 2007}}</ref> In 1999, [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] (BMI) listed it as one of the Top 100 Songs of the Century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archer2000.tripod.com/sbs/awardsbmi.html|title=Complete list of Top 100 Songs|publisher=archer2000.tripod.com|accessdate=21 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215221253/http://archer2000.tripod.com/sbs/awardsbmi.html|archivedate=15 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2000, it was listed at No.&nbsp;21 on the ''Rolling Stone''/MTV list of 100 Greatest Pop Songs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/rsmtv100.htm|title=Rolling Stone's and MTV's 200 Greatest Pop Songs|publisher=rockonthenet.com|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> and as No. 49 on [[VH1]]'s list of the 100 Greatest Rock Songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/vh1rocksongs.htm|title=VH1: 100 Greatest Rock Songs|publisher=rockonthenet.com|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> In 2001, it was ranked No.&nbsp;131 as one of the [[RIAA]]s [[Songs of the Century]], a list of the top 365 songs of the 20th century chosen with historical significance in mind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tcotrel.tripod.com/365songsbyrank.html |title=365 Songs by Rank |publisher=tcotrel.com |accessdate=1 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130045416/http://tcotrel.tripod.com/365songsbyrank.html |archivedate=30 January 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theassociation.net/txt-music5.html|title=The Association Admiration Aggregation|work=theassociation.net|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was ranked No.&nbsp;110 on the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine list of [[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref name=\"RS500GRSONGS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/rs |title=Rolling Stone Magazine's Top 500 Songs |accessdate=24 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524154958/http://www.metrolyrics.com/rs/4 |archivedate=24 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> At the same year, it was listed as No.&nbsp;79 on the All Time 885 Greatest Songs compiled by [[WXPN]] from listeners' votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xpn.org/music/885ATGS.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070531080329/http://www.xpn.org/music/885ATGS.php|url-status=dead|title=All-Time 885 Greatest Songs|archivedate=31 May 2007}}</ref> In January 2007, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Grammy Hall of Fame\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame |title=Grammy Hall of Fame Award |publisher=[[Grammy]] |accessdate=20 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707235113/http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame |archivedate=7 July 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> It was ranked as the 183rd greatest song of all time, as well as the 12th best song of 1967, by [[Acclaimed Music]].<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net|title=Acclaimed Music Top 3000 songs|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|date=27 May 2009}}</ref> It is also one of [[The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]].<ref name=\"The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.listsofbests.com/list/37752-500-songs-that-shaped-rock-and-roll|title=The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll|publisher=listsofbests.com|accessdate=23 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304151913/http://www.listsofbests.com/list/37752-500-songs-that-shaped-rock-and-roll|archivedate=4 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personnel ==\n\n* [[Van Morrison]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n* [[Eric Gale]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Gary Chester]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Russ Savakus]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Al Gorgoni]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Hugh McCracken]] \u2013 guitar\n* Garry Sherman \u2013 organ\n* The Sweet Inspirations \u2013 back-up vocals\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The song has been featured in several popular films, including the 1983 film ''[[The Big Chill (film)|The Big Chill]]'', the 1989 film ''[[Born on the Fourth of July (film)|Born on the Fourth of July]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/born_fourth.html|title=Fimtracks: Born on the Fourth of July|publisher=filmtracks.com|accessdate=27 October 2009}}</ref> and the 1991 film ''[[Sleeping with the Enemy]]'', starring [[Julia Roberts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0607341/|title=Van Morrison|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Mayor of London]] [[Boris Johnson]] included the song as one of his eight ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]] on 20 April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20051030.shtml|title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Boris Johnson|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref> [[Fashion designer]] [[Betty Jackson]] also included the song on her list on 28 April 2002,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20020428.shtml|title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Betty Jackson|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref> as did  British actor, comedian and singer [[Hugh Laurie]] on 23 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/0a7eb1db |title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Castaway: Hugh Laurie |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>\n* In April 2005, the [[White House]] announced that \"Brown Eyed Girl\" gets regular rotation on [[George W. Bush]]'s [[iPod]]. Morrison announced before a university performance in [[England]]: \"Yeah, it's good to hear things like that, you know. But I would have preferred if it was a new song.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7371946/renaissance_van |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114081855/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7371946/renaissance_van |archivedate=14 January 2009 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|title=Renaissance Van|accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n*A 2008 ''[[FoxTrot (comic strip)|FoxTrot]]'' strip portrays \"Brown Eyed Girl\", along with \"[[Eye of the Tiger]]\" by [[Survivor (band)|Survivor]] and \"[[My Eyes Adored You]]\" by [[The Four Seasons (band)|The Four Seasons]] as music played on the music site [[iTunes|EyeTunes]].\n* In March 2009, former US president [[Bill Clinton]] picked \"Brown Eyed Girl\" as top pick on his list of favourite ten tunes included on his signed iPod donated for a charity auction for musical victims of [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star-magazine.co.uk/posts/view/9191|title=Clinton picks Morrison & Simon for charity iPod|publisher=star magazine.co.uk|date=9 March 2009|accessdate=23 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001204604/http://star-magazine.co.uk/posts/view/9191|archivedate=1 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* The song was played at the end of the funeral for comedian [[Rik Mayall]] in June 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jun/19/rik-mayall-funeral-attended-stars-comedy|title=Rik Mayall funeral attended by stars of comedy|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=2014-06-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2016-05-10}}</ref>\n* The song is featured as a playable track in the 2015 video game ''[[Rock Band 4]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockband4.com|title=Rock Band 4 Core Soundtrack|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n* In [[Graeme Simsion]]'s 2017 novel ''[[The Best of Adam Sharp]]'', Adam is playing \"Brown Eyed Girl\" when he first meets Angelina, and it is the song he plays over the phone when they reconnect 22 years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.uk/articles/book-talk/soundtrack/2017/best-of-adam-sharp-playlist/|title=A playlist for reading The Best of Adam Sharp|publisher=Penguin|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801162359/https://www.penguin.co.uk/articles/book-talk/soundtrack/2017/best-of-adam-sharp-playlist/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! colspan=\"2\"| [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]\n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[UK Singles Chart]]\n|-\n| [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]\n| [[Hot Ringtones]]\n|-\n| 1967\n| 10<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/277711/van-morrison/chart?page=1&f=379 |title=Van Morrison - Chart history |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|-\n| 2006\n|\u2014\n| 18<ref name=\"allmusiccharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/van-morrison-mn0000307461/awards|title=Van Morrison - Awards|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n|\u2014\n|-\n| 2013\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n| 60<ref name=\"officialcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/van%20morrison/|title=VAN MORRISON|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other releases==\n\"Brown Eyed Girl\" was one of the songs included on the 1990 compilation album, ''[[The Best of Van Morrison]]''. It is one of the songs performed live at Morrison's concert of performance of 15 September 2006 at the [[Austin City Limits Festival]] and is included on the limited CD album, ''[[Live at Austin City Limits Festival]]''. \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was one of the nineteen songs featured on Van Morrison's 2007 compilation album, ''[[Van Morrison at the Movies \u2013 Soundtrack Hits]]''. The version on this compilation is a recent re-recording of the original version of the song. The original version is one of the hits on the 2007 compilation album, ''[[Still on Top \u2013 The Greatest Hits]]''. A live version of this song is featured on the 2008 reissue of the live double album ''[[It's Too Late to Stop Now]]''. Take 6 of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was released by Columbia's Legacy Records imprint in 1991 on compilation album ''[[Bang Masters]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brown Eyed Girl\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[El Chicano]]\n| album      = Celebration\n| B-side     = Mas zachate\n| released   = May 1972\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1972\n| studio     = [[The Sound Factory]], [[Los Angeles]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Brown eyed soul]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=11}}\n| label      = [[Kapp Records|Kapp]]\n| writer     = [[Van Morrison]]\n| producer   = Don Buday\n| prev_title = [[Sugar, Sugar]]\n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = Satisfy Me Woman\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brown Eyed Girl\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Iain Matthews|Ian Matthews]]\n| album      = Go For Broke\n| B-side     = Steamboat\n| released   = May 1976\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1976\n| studio     = Quadrofonic Studio, [[Nashville]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[soft rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=51}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Van Morrison]]\n| producer   = [[Norbert Putnam]], Glen Spreen\n| prev_title = [[I Don't Want to Talk About It]]\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = [[A Fool Like You]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n\n[[El Chicano]] remade \"Brown Eyed Girl\" for their 1972 album ''Celebration''. [[Kapp Records]] had invited music journalist Don Buday to produce the album, being impressed by Buday's writings on El Chicano: Buday had the group remake \"Brown Eyed Girl\" and also the [[Cream (band)|Cream]] hit \"[[I Feel Free]]\" \"[to try] to give [El Chicano] more of a rock-and-roll identity\".<ref>''Cashbox'' Vol 33 #45 (29 April 1972) \"Insight & Sound\" pp.14,32</ref> Journeyman recording engineer [[Val Garay]], who had his first engineering assignment producing ''Celebration'', would recall that \"Don got this brilliant idea of [remaking] 'Brown Eyed Girl'<span style=\"font-size:50%\">...</span>kind of like the 'Mexican Everly Brothers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tapeop.com/interviews/112/val-garay/|title=Val Garay: Linda Ronstadt, Kim Carnes, James Taylor|website=tapeop.com}}</ref> Released as the album's lead single, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" peaked at No. 45 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. [[Chicanismo]] scholar Dionne Espinoza opined that the El Chicano version of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" turned the song into \"an affirmation of the beauty of brown[-skinned] women\".<ref>{{cite book| title=Velvet Barrios: popular culture & Chicana/o sexualities| chapter=Tanto Tiempo Disfrutamos<span style=\"font-size:50%\">..</span>\": revisiting the gender & sexual politics of Chicano/a youth culture in East Los Angeles of the 1960s |first=Dionne| last=Espinoza| editor=Alicia Gaspar De Alba| publisher=Macmillan Palgrave| location=Basingstoke Hants| year=2003| page=90| isbn=978-1403960979}}</ref>\n\nBritish singer/songwriter [[Iain Matthews]] remade \"Brown Eyed Girl\" for his 1976 album ''Go for Broke''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/go-for-broke-mw0000899664|title=Go for Broke|first=Brett|last=Hartenbach|work=AllMusic|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> from which it was issued as the lead single, becoming a hit in the Netherlands (No. 22)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/weekchart.asp?year=1976&date=19760911&cat=s|title=Dutch Charts - dutchcharts.nl|website=dutchcharts.nl}}</ref> and in New Zealand (No. 25).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/|title=The Official New Zealand Music Chart|website=THE OFFICIAL NZ MUSIC CHART}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] hit (No. 13) for [[Jimmy Buffett]] as recorded for his ''[[One Particular Harbour]]'' album (1983),<ref name=\"whitburn2013\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944\u20132012|publisher=Record Research, Inc|page=318|year=2013|isbn=978-0-89820-203-8}}</ref> \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was a 1984 [[Hot Country Songs|C&W]] hit for [[Joe Stampley]] (No. 29),<ref name=\"whitburn2013\"/> while a 1980 remake by [[the Good Brothers]] was a hit in Canada on both the Country and Adult Contemporary charts, with respective chart peaks of No. 15 and No. 2.\n\nRecordings have also been made of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" as performed by a wide variety of other artists including [[Adele (singer)|Adele]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/music/great-british-songbook/songs/brown-eyed-girl/|publisher=[[BBC Radio 2]]|title=BBC - Radio 2's Great British Songbook: Brown Eyed Girl|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>[[John Anderson (musician)|John Anderson]],<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r307480|pure_url=yes}}|title=Takin' the Country Back > Overview|website=AllMusic|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> [[the Black Sorrows]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\">{{cite web|url=https://www.plagimusicali.net/archivio-cover|title=Archivio Cover - Plagi Musicali .Net|website=www.plagimusicali.net}}</ref> [[Busted (band)|Busted]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Billy Ray Cyrus]],<ref>''Billboard'' Billboard Vol 119 #30 (28 July 2007) p. 47</ref> [[Ellert Driessen]] ([[:nl:Ellert Driessen|nl]]),<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Bob Dylan]],{{citation needed| reason=no evident source| date=February 2019}} [[Everclear (band)|Everclear]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Caroline Jones (singer)|Caroline Jones]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whig.com/20190204/bare-feet-in-february-an-interview-with-caroline-jones|title='Bare Feet' in February: An interview with Caroline Jones|date=4 February 2019|website=Herald-Whig}}</ref> [[Roberto Jord\u00e1n]] (as \"La Chica De Los Ojos Caf\u00e9s\" <sub>Spanish</sub>),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45worlds.com/cdalbum/cd/888751692725|title=CD Album: Roberto Jord\u00e1n - Serie Del Recuerdo 2 En 1 (2016)|publisher=|via=www.45worlds.com}}</ref> [[Bertie Higgins]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ringsidereport.com/?p=2087|title=Singer and Songwriter Bertie Higgins Takes the RSR Readers on a Journey from Key Largo to the World of Boxing|date=14 April 2010|website=Ringside Report}}</ref> [[Ronan Keating]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/norfolk/content/articles/2005/07/26/music_review_ronan_keating_20050726.shtml|title=Ronan Keating at Blickling|publisher=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 October 2009}}</ref> [[Brian Kennedy (singer)|Brian Kennedy]], <ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p13387|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic: Brian Kennedy - All songs|publisher=allmusic.com|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> [[Lagwagon]],<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p39945|pure_url=yes}}|title=Lagwagon: Songs> All Songs|website=AllMusic|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> [[Glen Medeiros]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Reel Big Fish]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coversproject.com/artist/reel%20big%20fish/|title=Reel Big Fish Cover Songs|publisher=coversproject.com|accessdate=23 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615214828/http://www.coversproject.com/artist/reel%20big%20fish/|archive-date=15 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Johnny Rivers]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Shooting Gallery (band)|Shooting Gallery]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slamrocks.com/hanoi-rocks-la-vita-dopo-il-piu-bel-disastro-del-rock-and-roll-part-2/|title=Hanoi Rocks: la vita dopo il pi\u00f9 bel disastro del Rock And Roll (Part 2) - SLAM!|first=|last=Slam!|publisher=}}</ref> [[Bruce Springsteen]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Bruce-Springsteen-High-Hopes-Tour-2014/release/11774000|title=Bruce Springsteen - High Hopes Tour 2014|website=Discogs}}</ref> [[Steel Pulse]]<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> and [[U2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u2gigs.com/article410.html|title=U2 3 Nights Live: Second Night|publisher=u2gigs.com|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Collis, John (1996). ''Inarticulate Speech of the Heart'', Little Brown and Company, {{ISBN|0-306-80811-0}}\n* [[Erik Hage|Hage, Erik]] (2009). ''The Words and Music of Van Morrison'', Praeger Publishers, {{ISBN|978-0-313-35862-3}}\n* [[Clinton Heylin|Heylin, Clinton]] (2003). ''Can You Feel the Silence? Van Morrison: A New Biography'', Chicago Review Press {{ISBN|1-55652-542-7}}\n* [[Johnny Rogan|Rogan, Johnny]] (2006). ''[[Van Morrison: No Surrender]]'', London:Vintage Books {{ISBN|978-0-09-943183-1}}\n* [[Steve Turner (writer)|Turner, Steve]] (1993). ''[[Van Morrison: Too Late to Stop Now]]'', Viking Penguin, {{ISBN|0-670-85147-7}}\n* [[Paul Williams (Crawdaddy! creator)|Williams, Paul]] (1993). ''Rock and Roll: The 100 Best Singles'', Carroll & Graf Publishers, Inc., {{ISBN|0-88184-966-9}}\n* [[Ritchie Yorke|Yorke, Ritchie]] (1975). ''Into The Music'', London:Charisma Books, {{ISBN|0-85947-013-X}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|van-morrison|brown-eyed-girl}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Van Morrison singles}}\n\n[[Category:1967 singles]]\n[[Category:1984 singles]]\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:Van Morrison songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Hall of Fame Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Everclear (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Jimmy Buffett songs]]\n[[Category:Joe Stampley songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Van Morrison]]\n[[Category:1967 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bert Berns]]\n[[Category:Songs about sexuality]]\n[[Category:Bang Records singles]]\n[[Category:Songs about nostalgia]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the song|the South Korean girl group|Brown Eyed Girls}}\n{{about|the Van Morrison song|the song, \"Brown-Eyed Girl\"|The Golliwogs}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brown Eyed Girl\n| cover      = BrownEyedGirl.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Dutch 7-inch vinyl single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Van Morrison]]\n| album      = [[Blowin' Your Mind!]]\n| B-side     = Goodbye Baby\n| released   = {{Start date|1967|06}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single]]\n| recorded   = 28 March 1967\n| studio     = [[A & R Recording|A & R]], New York City\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]\n| length     = 3:05\n| label      =\n*[[London Records|London]] (UK)\n*[[Bang Records|Bang]] (US)\n| writer     = Van Morrison\n| producer   = [[Bert Berns]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Ro Ro Rosey\n| next_year  = 1967\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|UfmkgQRmmeE|\"Brown Eyed Girl\"}}\n | type   = single\n | header = Audio\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Brown Eyed Girl'''\" is a song by Northern Irish singer and songwriter [[Van Morrison]]. Written by Morrison and recorded in March 1967 for [[Bang Records]] owner and producer [[Bert Berns]], it was released as a single in June of the same year on the Bang label, peaking at number 10 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. The song spent a total of sixteen weeks on the chart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/van-morrison|title=Van Morrison Brown Eyed Girl Chart History|website=Billboard}}</ref> It featured [[the Sweet Inspirations]] singing [[Backing vocalist|back-up vocals]] and is considered to be Van Morrison's [[signature song]].<ref>Yorke, Into the Music, p. 42</ref> \"Brown Eyed Girl\" has remained a staple on [[classic rock]] radio, and has been covered by hundreds of bands over the decades.\n\n==Recording and title==\nAfter finishing his contract with [[Decca Records]] and the mid-1966 break-up of his band, [[Them (band)|Them]], Morrison returned to Belfast seeking a new recording company. When he received a phone call from [[Bert Berns]], owner of [[Bang Records]], who had produced a number of recordings with Them, he flew to New York City and hastily signed a contract (which biographer [[Clinton Heylin]] says probably still gives him sleepless nights).<ref>Heylin, ''Can You Feel the Silence''. p.144-147</ref> During a two-day recording session starting 28 March 1967, he recorded eight songs intended to be used as four singles.<ref>Turner, Too Late to Stop Now. p.76</ref> The recording session took place at A & R Studios and \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was captured on the 22nd take on the first day.<ref>Heylin, Can You Feel the Silence?, p. 152</ref> Of the musicians Berns had assembled, there were three guitarists \u2013 [[Eric Gale]], [[Hugh McCracken]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music-illuminati.com/interview-jeff-barry/|title=Interview: Jeff Barry|publisher=music-illuminati.com|date=29 January 2010|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref><ref>Rogan, ''No Surrender''. p.199</ref> and [[Al Gorgoni]] \u2013 plus bassist [[Russ Savakus]], pianist [[Paul Griffin (musician)|Paul Griffin]] and drummer [[Gary Chester]].<ref>Heylin, ''Can You Feel the Silence?''. p. 150</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gary-chester.com/biography.html |title=Meet Gary |publisher=gary-chester.com |accessdate=21 January 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116225941/http://www.gary-chester.com/biography.html |archivedate=16 January 2012 }}</ref> It was released as a single in mid-June 1967.<ref>Rogan, ''No Surrender''. p.201</ref>\n\nOriginally titled \"Brown-Skinned Girl\",<ref name = \"SpenceCut103\">{{cite web|url=http://www.folkways.si.edu/joseph-spence/the-complete-folkways-recordings-1958/caribbean-world/music/album/smithsonian|title=Smithsonian Folkways - Joseph Spence: The Complete Folkways Recordings, 1958|publisher=|accessdate=11 March 2016}}</ref> Morrison changed it to \"Brown Eyed Girl\" when he recorded it. Morrison remarked on the title change: \"That was just a mistake. It was a kind of Jamaican song. Calypso. It just slipped my mind [that] I changed the title.\"<ref name=\"CollisPage81\">Collis, Inarticulate Speech of the Heart. p81.</ref> \"After we'd recorded it, I looked at the tape box and didn't even notice that I'd changed the title. I looked at the box where I'd lain it down with my guitar and it said 'Brown Eyed Girl' on the tape box. It's just one of those things that happen.\"<ref>Rogan, No Surrender. p.43</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Independent on Sunday, ''Decoded songs and their meanings''|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/decoded-songs-and-their-meanings-2139733.html|date= 21 November 2010|accessdate=24 October 2013|location=London|work=The Independent|first=Paul|last=Bignell}}</ref>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n|filename=Van Morrison-Brown Eyed Girl.ogg\n|title=\"Brown Eyed Girl\"\n|description=An 18-second audio sample of Van Morrison's \"Brown Eyed Girl\"\n|format=[[Ogg]]}}\nThe song's nostalgic lyrics about a former love were considered too suggestive at the time to be played on many [[Radio broadcasting|radio stations]]. A radio-edit of the song was released which removed the lyrics \"making love in the green grass\", replacing them with \"laughin' and a-runnin', hey hey\" from a previous verse. This edited version appears on some copies of the compilation album ''[[The Best of Van Morrison]]''. However, the remastered album seems{{clarify|date=October 2013}} to have the [[Thomas Bowdler|bowdlerised]] lyrics in the packaging but the original \"racy\" lyrics on the disc. Lyrically, it \"shows early hints of the idealized pastoral landscapes that would flow through his songs through the decades, a tendency that links him to the Romantic poets, whom Morrison has cited as an influence\" according to music journalist Erik Hage.<ref>Hage, ''The Words and Music of Van Morrison'', pp. 33-34</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nBecause of a contract he signed with Bang Records without legal advice, Morrison states that he has never received any [[royalties]] for writing or recording this song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.martaypix.com/VAN_at_Rancho_Nicasio/VAN_Rancho.html|title=Van Morrison at Rancho Nicasio|publisher=martaypix.com|accessdate= 27 August 2008}}</ref> The contract made him liable for virtually all recording expenses incurred for all of his Bang Records recordings before royalties would be paid, and after those expenses were recouped, the revenue would become the \"subject of some highly creative accounting\".{{attribution needed|date=March 2018}}<ref>Heylin, Can You Feel the Silence. p.148</ref> Morrison vented frustration about this unjust contract in his sarcastic nonsense song \"The Big Royalty Check\". Morrison has stated that \"Brown Eyed Girl\" is not among his favourite songs, remarking \"it's not one of my best. I mean I've got about 300 songs that I think are better\".<ref>{{Cite video |title = TIME Magazine Interviews: Van Morrison | publisher = [[Time (magazine)|TIME]] |date =26 February 2009 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QVHbUPNcTiU |minutes=4:14 |accessdate=13 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nTo capitalise on the success of the single, producer Berns assembled the album ''[[Blowin' Your Mind!]]'' without Morrison's input or knowledge. Released in September 1967, the album contained the single as its lead-off track as well as songs recorded by Morrison at the March recording sessions for Berns. The album peaked at No. 182 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].\n\n==Legacy==\nMorrison's original recording of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" remains widely familiar today, as the uncensored version is regularly played by many \"[[oldies]]\" and \"[[classic rock]]\" radio stations. In 2005, Morrison received a Million-Air certificate by [[Broadcast Music Incorporated|BMI]] as a \"Top European Writer\" for reaching 7 million US radio and television airplays for \"Brown Eyed Girl\" and again in 2007, Morrison was awarded another Million-Air certificate by BMI for 8 million air plays of \"Brown Eyed Girl\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/334626|title=BMI Honors Top European Writers|date=28 November 2005|accessdate=23 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114065908/http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/334626|archive-date=14 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/535578|title=Peter Gabriel Receives Top Honor at BMI Awards|publisher=BMI|date=16 October 2007|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> In 2009, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was at the top of the list for most played songs at the BMI London awards winning a Million-Air certificate for 9 million air plays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmi.com/news/entry/539750|title=BMI London Awards|date=9 October 2009|publisher=BMI|accessdate=13 April 2011}}</ref> In 2011, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" joined an elite group of songs as it was honoured for having 10 million US radio air plays and therefore becoming one of the ten songs that have been registered with BMI that have received that number of radio plays.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/my-10-million-radio-plays-brown-eyed-girl-2896314.html|title=My 10 million radio plays Brown Eyed Girl|journal=[[Irish Independent]]|date=5 October 2011|accessdate=21 January 2011}}</ref> As of 2015, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" remains the most downloaded and most played song of the entire 1960s decade.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6472929/revisionist-history-valentines-day-edition-captain-tennille |title=Revisionist History, Valentine's Day Edition: Captain & Tennille Crunches Aerosmith, Van Morrison Boots Lulu |last=Appel |first=Rich |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=14 February 2015 |accessdate=15 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Paul Williams (Crawdaddy! creator)|Paul Williams]] included \"Brown Eyed Girl\" in his book ''Rock and Roll: The 100 Best Singles'',<ref>Williams, Rock and Roll: The 100 Best Singles. p. 122</ref> writing that:\n\n<blockquote>\"I was going to say this is a song about sex, and it is, and a song about youth and growing up, and memory, and it's also\u2014very much and very wonderfully\u2014a song about singing.\"</blockquote>\n\nThis song proved to be the impetus for Morrison's career. It was his first single after leaving his position as lead singer for the [[Belfast]]-formed [[Them (band)|Them]] and led to his relocation to the United States and an eventual [[recording contract|contract]] with [[Warner Bros. Records]], where he recorded his career-defining [[album]], ''[[Astral Weeks]]''.\n\n==Critical acclaim and influence==\n[[Dave Marsh]] in his 1989 book, ''The Heart of Rock and Soul, The 1001 Greatest Singles Ever'', rated it No.&nbsp;386.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/dmarsh_1001.htm |title= Dave Marsh the 1001 greatest Singles Ever |publisher=rocklistmusic.co.uk |accessdate=8 April 2007}}</ref> In 1999, [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] (BMI) listed it as one of the Top 100 Songs of the Century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archer2000.tripod.com/sbs/awardsbmi.html|title=Complete list of Top 100 Songs|publisher=archer2000.tripod.com|accessdate=21 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120215221253/http://archer2000.tripod.com/sbs/awardsbmi.html|archivedate=15 February 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2000, it was listed at No.&nbsp;21 on the ''Rolling Stone''/MTV list of 100 Greatest Pop Songs<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/rsmtv100.htm|title=Rolling Stone's and MTV's 200 Greatest Pop Songs|publisher=rockonthenet.com|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> and as No. 49 on [[VH1]]'s list of the 100 Greatest Rock Songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/2000/vh1rocksongs.htm|title=VH1: 100 Greatest Rock Songs|publisher=rockonthenet.com|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref> In 2001, it was ranked No.&nbsp;131 as one of the [[RIAA]]s [[Songs of the Century]], a list of the top 365 songs of the 20th century chosen with historical significance in mind.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tcotrel.tripod.com/365songsbyrank.html |title=365 Songs by Rank |publisher=tcotrel.com |accessdate=1 January 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130045416/http://tcotrel.tripod.com/365songsbyrank.html |archivedate=30 January 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theassociation.net/txt-music5.html|title=The Association Admiration Aggregation|work=theassociation.net|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was ranked No.&nbsp;110 on the ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine list of [[500 Greatest Songs of All Time]].<ref name=\"RS500GRSONGS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metrolyrics.com/rs |title=Rolling Stone Magazine's Top 500 Songs |accessdate=24 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130524154958/http://www.metrolyrics.com/rs/4 |archivedate=24 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> At the same year, it was listed as No.&nbsp;79 on the All Time 885 Greatest Songs compiled by [[WXPN]] from listeners' votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xpn.org/music/885ATGS.php|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070531080329/http://www.xpn.org/music/885ATGS.php|url-status=dead|title=All-Time 885 Greatest Songs|archivedate=31 May 2007}}</ref> In January 2007, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was inducted into the [[Grammy Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"Grammy Hall of Fame\">{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame |title=Grammy Hall of Fame Award |publisher=[[Grammy]] |accessdate=20 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150707235113/http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame |archivedate=7 July 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> It was ranked as the 183rd greatest song of all time, as well as the 12th best song of 1967, by [[Acclaimed Music]].<ref name=\"Acclaimed Music\">{{cite web|url=http://www.acclaimedmusic.net|title=Acclaimed Music Top 3000 songs|publisher=[[Acclaimed Music]]|date=27 May 2009}}</ref> It is also one of [[The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll]].<ref name=\"The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll\">{{cite web|url=http://www.listsofbests.com/list/37752-500-songs-that-shaped-rock-and-roll|title=The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame's 500 Songs that Shaped Rock and Roll|publisher=listsofbests.com|accessdate=23 October 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110304151913/http://www.listsofbests.com/list/37752-500-songs-that-shaped-rock-and-roll|archivedate=4 March 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Personnel ==\n\n* [[Van Morrison]] \u2013 vocals, guitar\n* [[Eric Gale]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Gary Chester]] \u2013 drums\n* [[Russ Savakus]] \u2013 bass guitar\n* [[Al Gorgoni]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Hugh McCracken]] \u2013 guitar\n* Garry Sherman \u2013 organ\n* The Sweet Inspirations \u2013 back-up vocals\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The song has been featured in several popular films, including the 1983 film ''[[The Big Chill (film)|The Big Chill]]'', the 1989 film ''[[Born on the Fourth of July (film)|Born on the Fourth of July]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/born_fourth.html|title=Fimtracks: Born on the Fourth of July|publisher=filmtracks.com|accessdate=27 October 2009}}</ref> and the 1991 film ''[[Sleeping with the Enemy]]'', starring [[Julia Roberts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0607341/|title=Van Morrison|publisher=IMDb|accessdate=8 July 2015}}</ref>\n* [[Mayor of London]] [[Boris Johnson]] included the song as one of his eight ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' on [[BBC Radio 4]] on 20 April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20051030.shtml|title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Boris Johnson|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref> [[Fashion designer]] [[Betty Jackson]] also included the song on her list on 28 April 2002,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20020428.shtml|title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Betty Jackson|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 October 2009}}</ref> as did  British actor, comedian and singer [[Hugh Laurie]] on 23 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/features/desert-island-discs/castaway/0a7eb1db |title=Desert Island Discs \u2013 Castaway: Hugh Laurie |publisher=BBC |date= |accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>\n* In April 2005, the [[White House]] announced that \"Brown Eyed Girl\" gets regular rotation on [[George W. Bush]]'s [[iPod]]. Morrison announced before a university performance in [[England]]: \"Yeah, it's good to hear things like that, you know. But I would have preferred if it was a new song.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7371946/renaissance_van |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114081855/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7371946/renaissance_van |archivedate=14 January 2009 |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|title=Renaissance Van|accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref>\n*A 2008 ''[[FoxTrot (comic strip)|FoxTrot]]'' strip portrays \"Brown Eyed Girl\", along with \"[[Eye of the Tiger]]\" by [[Survivor (band)|Survivor]] and \"[[My Eyes Adored You]]\" by [[The Four Seasons (band)|The Four Seasons]] as music played on the music site [[iTunes|EyeTunes]].\n* In March 2009, former US president [[Bill Clinton]] picked \"Brown Eyed Girl\" as top pick on his list of favourite ten tunes included on his signed iPod donated for a charity auction for musical victims of [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://star-magazine.co.uk/posts/view/9191|title=Clinton picks Morrison & Simon for charity iPod|publisher=star magazine.co.uk|date=9 March 2009|accessdate=23 January 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001204604/http://star-magazine.co.uk/posts/view/9191|archivedate=1 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* The song was played at the end of the funeral for comedian [[Rik Mayall]] in June 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2014/jun/19/rik-mayall-funeral-attended-stars-comedy|title=Rik Mayall funeral attended by stars of comedy|last=Morris|first=Steven|date=2014-06-19|work=The Guardian|access-date=2016-05-10}}</ref>\n* The song is featured as a playable track in the 2015 video game ''[[Rock Band 4]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rockband4.com|title=Rock Band 4 Core Soundtrack|accessdate=21 February 2018}}</ref>\n* In [[Graeme Simsion]]'s 2017 novel ''[[The Best of Adam Sharp]]'', Adam is playing \"Brown Eyed Girl\" when he first meets Angelina, and it is the song he plays over the phone when they reconnect 22 years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.penguin.co.uk/articles/book-talk/soundtrack/2017/best-of-adam-sharp-playlist/|title=A playlist for reading The Best of Adam Sharp|publisher=Penguin|accessdate=1 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170801162359/https://www.penguin.co.uk/articles/book-talk/soundtrack/2017/best-of-adam-sharp-playlist/|archive-date=1 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! colspan=\"2\"| [[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]\n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[UK Singles Chart]]\n|-\n| [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]\n| [[Hot Ringtones]]\n|-\n| 1967\n| 10<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/277711/van-morrison/chart?page=1&f=379 |title=Van Morrison - Chart history |magazine=Billboard |accessdate=25 October 2013}}</ref>\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n|-\n| 2006\n|\u2014\n| 18<ref name=\"allmusiccharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/van-morrison-mn0000307461/awards|title=Van Morrison - Awards|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n|\u2014\n|-\n| 2013\n|\u2014\n|\u2014\n| 60<ref name=\"officialcharts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/_/van%20morrison/|title=VAN MORRISON|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=16 June 2013}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other releases==\n\"Brown Eyed Girl\" was one of the songs included on the 1990 compilation album, ''[[The Best of Van Morrison]]''. It is one of the songs performed live at Morrison's concert of performance of 15 September 2006 at the [[Austin City Limits Festival]] and is included on the limited CD album, ''[[Live at Austin City Limits Festival]]''. \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was one of the nineteen songs featured on Van Morrison's 2007 compilation album, ''[[Van Morrison at the Movies \u2013 Soundtrack Hits]]''. The version on this compilation is a recent re-recording of the original version of the song. The original version is one of the hits on the 2007 compilation album, ''[[Still on Top \u2013 The Greatest Hits]]''. A live version of this song is featured on the 2008 reissue of the live double album ''[[It's Too Late to Stop Now]]''. Take 6 of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was released by Columbia's Legacy Records imprint in 1991 on compilation album ''[[Bang Masters]]''.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brown Eyed Girl\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[El Chicano]]\n| album      = Celebration\n| B-side     = Mas zachate\n| released   = May 1972\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1972\n| studio     = [[The Sound Factory]], [[Los Angeles]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Brown eyed soul]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=11}}\n| label      = [[Kapp Records|Kapp]]\n| writer     = [[Van Morrison]]\n| producer   = Don Buday\n| prev_title = [[Sugar, Sugar]]\n| prev_year  = 1971\n| next_title = Satisfy Me Woman\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brown Eyed Girl\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Iain Matthews|Ian Matthews]]\n| album      = Go For Broke\n| B-side     = Steamboat\n| released   = May 1976\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7-inch]]\n| recorded   = 1976\n| studio     = Quadrofonic Studio, [[Nashville]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[soft rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=3|s=51}}\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = [[Van Morrison]]\n| producer   = [[Norbert Putnam]], Glen Spreen\n| prev_title = [[I Don't Want to Talk About It]]\n| prev_year  = 1975\n| next_title = [[A Fool Like You]]\n| next_year  = 1976\n}}\n\n[[El Chicano]] remade \"Brown Eyed Girl\" for their 1972 album ''Celebration''. [[Kapp Records]] had invited music journalist Don Buday to produce the album, being impressed by Buday's writings on El Chicano: Buday had the group remake \"Brown Eyed Girl\" and also the [[Cream (band)|Cream]] hit \"[[I Feel Free]]\" \"[to try] to give [El Chicano] more of a rock-and-roll identity\".<ref>''Cashbox'' Vol 33 #45 (29 April 1972) \"Insight & Sound\" pp.14,32</ref> Journeyman recording engineer [[Val Garay]], who had his first engineering assignment producing ''Celebration'', would recall that \"Don got this brilliant idea of [remaking] 'Brown Eyed Girl'<span style=\"font-size:50%\">...</span>kind of like the 'Mexican Everly Brothers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tapeop.com/interviews/112/val-garay/|title=Val Garay: Linda Ronstadt, Kim Carnes, James Taylor|website=tapeop.com}}</ref> Released as the album's lead single, \"Brown Eyed Girl\" peaked at No. 45 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. [[Chicanismo]] scholar Dionne Espinoza opined that the El Chicano version of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" turned the song into \"an affirmation of the beauty of brown[-skinned] women\".<ref>{{cite book| title=Velvet Barrios: popular culture & Chicana/o sexualities| chapter=Tanto Tiempo Disfrutamos<span style=\"font-size:50%\">..</span>\": revisiting the gender & sexual politics of Chicano/a youth culture in East Los Angeles of the 1960s |first=Dionne| last=Espinoza| editor=Alicia Gaspar De Alba| publisher=Macmillan Palgrave| location=Basingstoke Hants| year=2003| page=90| isbn=978-1403960979}}</ref>\n\nBritish singer/songwriter [[Iain Matthews]] remade \"Brown Eyed Girl\" for his 1976 album ''Go for Broke''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/go-for-broke-mw0000899664|title=Go for Broke|first=Brett|last=Hartenbach|work=AllMusic|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref> from which it was issued as the lead single, becoming a hit in the Netherlands (No. 22)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dutchcharts.nl/weekchart.asp?year=1976&date=19760911&cat=s|title=Dutch Charts - dutchcharts.nl|website=dutchcharts.nl}}</ref> and in New Zealand (No. 25).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/|title=The Official New Zealand Music Chart|website=THE OFFICIAL NZ MUSIC CHART}}</ref>\n\nAn [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Adult Contemporary]] hit (No. 13) for [[Jimmy Buffett]] as recorded for his ''[[One Particular Harbour]]'' album (1983),<ref name=\"whitburn2013\">{{cite book|last=Whitburn|first=Joel|title=Hot Country Songs 1944\u20132012|publisher=Record Research, Inc|page=318|year=2013|isbn=978-0-89820-203-8}}</ref> \"Brown Eyed Girl\" was a 1984 [[Hot Country Songs|C&W]] hit for [[Joe Stampley]] (No. 29),<ref name=\"whitburn2013\"/> while a 1980 remake by [[the Good Brothers]] was a hit in Canada on both the Country and Adult Contemporary charts, with respective chart peaks of No. 15 and No. 2.\n\nRecordings have also been made of \"Brown Eyed Girl\" as performed by a wide variety of other artists including [[Adele (singer)|Adele]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/music/great-british-songbook/songs/brown-eyed-girl/|publisher=[[BBC Radio 2]]|title=BBC - Radio 2's Great British Songbook: Brown Eyed Girl|accessdate=21 January 2012}}</ref>[[John Anderson (musician)|John Anderson]],<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r307480|pure_url=yes}}|title=Takin' the Country Back > Overview|website=AllMusic|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> [[the Black Sorrows]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\">{{cite web|url=https://www.plagimusicali.net/archivio-cover|title=Archivio Cover - Plagi Musicali .Net|website=www.plagimusicali.net}}</ref> [[Busted (band)|Busted]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Billy Ray Cyrus]],<ref>''Billboard'' Billboard Vol 119 #30 (28 July 2007) p. 47</ref> [[Ellert Driessen]] ([[:nl:Ellert Driessen|nl]]),<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Bob Dylan]],{{citation needed| reason=no evident source| date=February 2019}} [[Everclear (band)|Everclear]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Caroline Jones (singer)|Caroline Jones]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whig.com/20190204/bare-feet-in-february-an-interview-with-caroline-jones|title='Bare Feet' in February: An interview with Caroline Jones|date=4 February 2019|website=Herald-Whig}}</ref> [[Roberto Jord\u00e1n]] (as \"La Chica De Los Ojos Caf\u00e9s\" <sub>Spanish</sub>),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45worlds.com/cdalbum/cd/888751692725|title=CD Album: Roberto Jord\u00e1n - Serie Del Recuerdo 2 En 1 (2016)|publisher=|via=www.45worlds.com}}</ref> [[Bertie Higgins]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ringsidereport.com/?p=2087|title=Singer and Songwriter Bertie Higgins Takes the RSR Readers on a Journey from Key Largo to the World of Boxing|date=14 April 2010|website=Ringside Report}}</ref> [[Ronan Keating]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/norfolk/content/articles/2005/07/26/music_review_ronan_keating_20050726.shtml|title=Ronan Keating at Blickling|publisher=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 October 2009}}</ref> [[Brian Kennedy (singer)|Brian Kennedy]], <ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p13387|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic: Brian Kennedy - All songs|publisher=allmusic.com|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> [[Lagwagon]],<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p39945|pure_url=yes}}|title=Lagwagon: Songs> All Songs|website=AllMusic|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref> [[Glen Medeiros]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Reel Big Fish]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coversproject.com/artist/reel%20big%20fish/|title=Reel Big Fish Cover Songs|publisher=coversproject.com|accessdate=23 January 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120615214828/http://www.coversproject.com/artist/reel%20big%20fish/|archive-date=15 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Johnny Rivers]],<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> [[Shooting Gallery (band)|Shooting Gallery]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slamrocks.com/hanoi-rocks-la-vita-dopo-il-piu-bel-disastro-del-rock-and-roll-part-2/|title=Hanoi Rocks: la vita dopo il pi\u00f9 bel disastro del Rock And Roll (Part 2) - SLAM!|first=|last=Slam!|publisher=}}</ref> [[Bruce Springsteen]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Bruce-Springsteen-High-Hopes-Tour-2014/release/11774000|title=Bruce Springsteen - High Hopes Tour 2014|website=Discogs}}</ref> [[Steel Pulse]]<ref name=\"PlagiMusicali\"/> and [[U2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.u2gigs.com/article410.html|title=U2 3 Nights Live: Second Night|publisher=u2gigs.com|accessdate=25 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography=